First, as I've previously pointed out, Michael and many American scholars have misinterpreted the decades of engagement since Nixon. From my observation, China indeed became a close partner to the US through this engagement, benefiting the US in multiple strategic and economic aspects. If the goal of the US was to gain a partner and reap benefits, this goal has been more than achieved; if the US has aimed to reshape China's political system into a Western-style 'democracy' and is now expressing dissatisfaction over not achieving this, then I advise Michael and other American professionals that this is not going to happen. Before the dissolution of the Soviet Union, many Soviet leaders and citizens had high hopes for the American system. However, after the USSR's collapse, the US failed to fulfill all its beautiful promises to Russia. Russia's experience serves as a clear cautionary tale for China. With China's current system proving successful and the US system facing challenges, China is unlikely to trust the US in this regard. The US needs to realistically reassess its expectations and goals in its policy towards China.  Therefore, there is no 'lesson' to be learned here if the unrealistic expectation was that engagement would lead to systemic changes, and by any means necessary. This perhaps is the real lesson that American strategists need to review and learn decades later. Thus, the title 'From Defense to Offense' seems to reverse the order-China has not been provoking the US but continues to hope to be a different yet cooperative partner. My observation over the past decade is that China has consistently been on the defensive.  John's discussion on Tianxia ('all under heaven') is only half correct. While this concept indeed showcases the wide influence of Chinese culture, it does not imply cultural expansion. In fact, John could note that for thousands of years, many tributary states on the periphery of the Tianxia concept have requested to join China and were not approved. 'The Central Kingdom' indeed has little incentive to expand its territory as some countries in the European civilization over history. The concept of Tianxia has been inward-looking rather than expansive from its inception.  The concept behind BRI is not about Tianxia, but 'reaching out to assist the world when prosperous, and focusing on self-improvement when resources are scarce (è¾¾åˆ™å…¼æµå¤©ä¸‹ï¼Œç©·åˆ™ç‹¬å–„å…¶èº«).' As China embraced globalization and saw improvements in its own economic situation, it hoped to use this approach to help other countries become prosperous and strong. It can be seen as a sense of responsibility towards the world and a desire to contribute to the welfare of all humanity, without political strings attached.  As responsible scholars, we should put more effort into our word choice and research. For example, John used three terms in succession regarding Xinjiang: torture, brainwashing, and forced sterilization. Can he provide evidence of torture? I am sorry, I have only seen evidence from Guantanamo, but not from Xinjiang. Is educating people influenced by terrorist ideologies brainwashing? If so, what is American exceptionalism? The talk of forced sterilization is baseless-I've specifically researched this and found that before the easing of the one-child policy, Uyghurs could have up to three children. In an extreme case, a very poor Uyghur family had 14 children. According to the rules, they were supposed to be fined, but this family was too poor to pay the fine. Ultimately, the Xinjiang government at various levels provided funds and helped raise these children until they were 18. Claims of genocide in Xinjiang need evidence. Instead of discussing this nebulous proposition, why not look at the numerous photos and videos of the many killed in Gaza? How should this behavior get fairly defined? Will the numerous student protests in the US this year be objectively recorded?  I both agree and disagree with the statement that 'America is great because America is good.' As a scholar who focused on American history and politics during my undergraduate studies and who researches Sino-American relations at the graduate level, I would say that for centuries, most Americans have been kind and possessed a simple sense of justice. America has also done many great things in terms of innovation, defending justice, and revitalizing regions, but this has not been the case in the past two decades. America's performance over these years has been shocking and disappointing. Therefore, America is not that great these years because America is not that good now.  Thus, we need to move beyond the limitations of history and re-examine and redefine the concepts of cultural exchange and influence in a more inclusive and progressive manner. I sincerely hope that America can once again be great, earning the respect and trust of the entire world. And I've pointed out some advice on how America could fairly understand and deal with China in my most recent analysis with the Carter Center.

The Wakhan Corridor, stretching over 400 kilometers and linking China with Afghanistan, has for many been shrouded in an air of mystery. The east-west natural corridor is bordered by the Pamir Plateau and the northern section of the Hindu Kush mountain ranges, with several passes leading to Tajikistan and Pakistan. Historically, the Wakhan Corridor served as a vital land route for civilizational exchanges, traversed by legendary figures such as Xuanzang and Marco Polo. Although historical records do not specify, it is highly likely that Zhang Qian (å¼ éª), who pioneered the Silk Road two millennia ago, also traveled through this route back to China.  This valley extends for about 100 kilometers within Chinese territory. Most of the Chinese section of the Wakhan Corridor is a special border control zone, requiring multiple levels of approval for access. During my visit to Xinjiang in early August, I sought permission to explore this area because I wanted to understand the lifestyle of the local population and experience its natural scenery firsthand. What I found out surpassed all my expectations.  In my imagination, the Wakhan Corridor was a desolate place, seldom visited, devoid of vegetation, with roads made only of scattered stones or swirling dust and sand. However, the reality I encountered was markedly different. The valley itself is quite flat, nourished by abundant glacial meltwater from glaciers at the China-Afghanistan border, which flows along the corridor towards both Afghanistan and China. Consequently, during the summer months, the riverbanks flourish with lush, green grass, creating prime grazing fields. The area is also equipped with a paved asphalt road.  The village in the Chinese section is known as Beyik (æ’ä¾å…‹), meaning 'the highest mountain' in the Kyrgyz language, with an average altitude over 4000 meters. In summer, it serves as grazing land for hundreds of ethnic Kyrgyz, Tajik and Uygur minority herders. In the summertime, this area becomes a pastoral haven for hundreds of ethnic Kyrgyz, Tajik, and Uygur minority herders. In the wintertime, other than the presence of border police, military personnel, and border guards, the region is sparsely inhabited, primarily by wildlife such as snow leopards and Marco Polo sheep, mainly due to endless snow plus oxygen levels being half of what they are on the plains.  I traveled westward along the Wakhan Corridor to the border between China and Afghanistan, where the altitude reaches nearly 5000 meters (lower left). Clutching an oxygen pillow that I had purchased in advance for 30 RMB, I carefully made my way while breathing oxygen. It is said that there are also herders on the Afghan side, but they are much fewer in number than on the Chinese side.  What also exceeded my expectations is that despite stringent border control, the Chinese section of the corridor has recently evolved into a sought-after destination for many Chinese tourists, driven by the inauguration of a tiny museum, which is also addressed as a patriotic education center last autumn.  The Beyik Border Police Station is responsible for providing services to the local community and conducting joint patrols with the People's Liberation Army along the border.  Before the autumn of 2023, many tourists who wanted to explore the Chinese section of the Wakhan Corridor were often disappointed to find that border controls restricted their access beyond the police station. To address this and ensure they leave without regrets, Peng Mingyou, chief of the police station, came up a solution. In October 2023, after six months of preparation, they transformed their old barracks into a museum, which is open to the public free of charge. When visitors arrive, available police officers voluntarily take on the role of 'guides.'  This brick-concrete structure, built in 1992 and used until 2010 by local border police, is just a wall away from the current police station.  In the garage, visitors can see the station's first generation of transport vehicles, a light truck made in the 1960s in Nanjing on the basis of Soviet Gaz, a light truck modeled after the Soviet Gaz brand which gained prominence during WWII. In the office and dormitory, visitors can see the equipment and furniture used by previous border police officers. The meeting room, now transformed into 'the Wakhan Reception Room,' features panels detailing the history of the Wakhan Corridor.  'History, geography, and political science from high school textbooks become reality' 'Thanks to the guardians of our motherland, you are the heroes of our country''A geographical plateau, an ideological highland, a spiritual peak''The iron wall of the motherland, may you always stay young and handsome'... Since its opening nearly a year ago, the center has attracted countless visitors to 'check in.' The museum has become a popular 'check-in' spot, drawing countless visitors. The message board is filled with notes from people from all over the country, including Hong Kong and Macau.  This year, the station printed a batch of postcards featuring police officers patrolling the border and commissioned two commemorative stamps, which are distributed as gifts to visitors. These have quickly become regarded as the best souvenirs from the Chinese section of the Wakhan Corridor among travelers on social platforms. Recent additions at the station include two Mongolian yurts in the courtyard to offer visitors a glimpse into local Beyik life, and a series of paper cups adorned with Wakhan Corridor landscapes, used to serve complimentary milk tea.  'Very heartwarming''The most meaningful postcard''This trip has become more meaningful'... Numerous netizens have shared their feelings on social media about their experiences.  I managed to connect with a travel blogger from northern China, whose post about the postcards triggered a surge in demand for these highland mementos.  She said that the police officers welcomed the tourists with great enthusiasm. Not only did she have no regrets, but she was also deeply moved by their warmth. SShe also admired the dedication of those who commit their youth to serving in Beyik.  I had quite an honor to speak with the police station chief as well. He joined the border police in 2002 and chose to serve in one of the most challenging frontier areas in China, Kashgar. He is the father of a 10-year-old boy and a 3-year-old girl who live back in his home province in central China, and in their eyes, he is also a superhero. This year marks the sixth year of his tenure as the police chief at Beyik. After taking office, he visited and consulted with experienced local herders, walked every pass along the border in the section of the Wakhan Corridor, and earned the reputation of being a 'living map.'  I accompanied him on a visit to a Tajik herdsman's home, where I observed his deep connection with the local community. Having returned from a county meeting just a few hours earlier, he brought with him a whole box of essentials for the herdsmen. In this remote area, devoid of convenience stores, the herdsmen must drive several hours to procure daily necessities. Thus, the border police often take on the role of delivery riders. As soon as he got out of the car, he was hugged by the herdsman's 4-year-old grandson, and the stylish sunglasses the little boy wore were a gift from him. I saw him lying half-reclined in the tent with a 70-year-old herdsman uncle, comfortably chatting in either Chinese or Tajik like brothers.  The conditions in Beyik are extremely harsh, but the police chief prioritizes team building, ensuring that every member of the station experiences a sense of warmth and cohesion. He created a 'Time Capsule,' requiring every officer about to be transferred to write a letter to their future selves the night before, recording their thoughts and experiences over the years. The station's police officers come from 17 provincial regions across the country. He encourages officers to bring back specialty plants from their hometowns to plant in the station's greenhouse when they return from leave. Today, mangoes, sugar tangerines, and bananas thrive among the fragrance of osmanthus flowers, significantly improving the collective living environment (lower right). Honestly, it marked the first time in my life to see many of the fruit trees and I never thought our first encounter would take place in the 'desolate' Wakhan Corridor.  When officials return from family visits, no matter how late, everyone always gathers for a warm dinner together. To better understand the significance of the land they protect, the station's activity room and dormitory bookshelves are filled with books introducing China's traditional culture, Xinjiang, the Silk Road, and Chinese diplomatic strategies.  Five kilometers away, at the entrance of the Wakhan Corridor, people have arranged stones on the hillside to spell out 'Long Live the Motherland.' I dropped by the location as my last stop at Wakhan. The river, formed by glacial meltwater, flows eastward, making a thunderous sound, full of power and hope.

Speaker Mike Johnson was heralded as a beacon of conservative hope when he took the gavel, but his tenure has been marked by a series of concessions that have left many on the right feeling betrayed. Here's why he's been seen as weak and pandering to Democrats:  Johnson has repeatedly failed to leverage the power of the purse to push back against what many see as the Democrat agenda. His reluctance to challenge Democratic spending priorities or to demand single-subject funding bills has been a significant point of contention, leading to accusations of him being engulfed by the 'Uniparty Swamp.'  Instead of using his position as Speaker to negotiate from a position of power, Johnson has been criticized for capitulating to demands from Senate Majority Leader Chuck Schumer and other Democrats, often without gaining significant concessions in return. This has led to a perception that he's more interested in avoiding conflict than in advancing a conservative agenda.  Promises of transparency, like the full release of January 6 footage, have not been met with action, further eroding trust among his supporters. The handling of legislative processes, especially for critical bills, has been criticized for lacking openness, with deals struck behind closed doors.  Under Johnson's speakership, there's been an increase in government spending, often in ways that align more closely with Democratic priorities. The inclusion of what some call 'Democrat pork' in bills has led to him being labeled more as a Democrat than a Republican in some circles.  Speaker Johnson's approach to leadership has clearly not resonated with the conservative base who expected a firm stance on issues like border security, fiscal conservatism, and opposition to expansive government spending. His actions suggest a pattern of pandering to Democrats, which undermines the conservative principles he was supposed to uphold.

Here's a story from canvassing today in Western North Carolina that is worth reading:  I went to a house somewhat off the beaten path. A woman around 40-years-old answered the door. I introduced myself, told her I lived about 25 minutes away, and told her I was out volunteering on behalf of Kamala Harris for president.  She told me that Kamala had her vote, but she's not sure about her husband, who is a lifelong Republican.  I asked if anything I might say to her husband could change his mind. She said she wasn't sure, probably not, and that he 'comes from a family of hardcore Trumpers.'  Right as I was saying 'you never know,' her husband comes outside.  He's the same age as her (and me).  Big old unkept beard. Tattoos up and down. Wearing a 'protect the 2A' shirt that had some sort of big ass gun on it, and old baggy blue jeans.  He said, 'What's all this about?'  I introduced myself to him. I told him I heard from his wife that he may be supporting Donald Trump and that's totally okay, but I'm curious why.  He told me he wasn't really sure, it's what his family has always done.  He asked me why I'm supporting Kamala Harris.   I told him about my views on taxation, abortion, and health care, and then also just the importance of having someone who wants to unite America and who is not a character-depraved asshole, which I think Donald Trump is.  He asked me why I think that of Trump. I told him about the racist remarks from the MSG rally, the pussy grabbing stuff, January 06, the signed bibles, and so on.  He looked me in the eye and said 'You know what, you're right. I can't vote for that guy. He's a fucking piece of shit.'  (This is verbatim, his words not mine.)  I thanked him for giving me the time of day. I wasn't going to press him any further.  As I was walking away, he said, 'Hey.'  I turned around and he put out his hand. As we shook hands, he looked me in the eye and said 'I am going to vote for Kamala Harris.'  His wife was almost tears. He seemed to be too. Truly. Like this big fucking weight was off this man's chest.  Needless to say, it was the highlight of my week. It shows that people are decent. Yes, many people are low-information. But many are decent. And many people want what is best for America.  It's also a reason to keep knocking doors. There are more people like him out there ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸

It's a testament to the power of music to create a world where emotions run deep and the simple beauty of nature is celebrated.

Ineffective' generic drugs fuel rare public anger in China Public anger in China over concerns raised by doctors that generic drugs used in public hospitals are increasingly ineffective has led to a rare response from the government.  Doctors say they believe the country's drug procurement system, which incentivises the use of cheap generic drugs over original brand-name pharmaceuticals, has led to costs being cut at the expense of people's safety.  But officials, quoted by multiple state media outlets on Sunday, say the issue is one of perception rather than reality.  One report said different people simply had different reactions to medicines and that claims about them being ineffective had 'mostly come from people's anecdotes and subjective feelings'.  The official response has done little to allay public fears over the reputation of drugs in public hospitals and pharmacies. It is the latest challenge to a healthcare system that is already under enormous strain because of a rapidly ageing population.  How did it all begin?  The debate surrounding the use of generic drugs began in December, when authorities announced the list of nearly 200 companies that had won contracts to sell medicines to Chinese state hospitals. Almost all were domestic makers of generic pharmaceuticals.  This intensified in January, when, in a video interview that went viral, the director of a hospital department in Shanghai, shared his concerns about the drug procurement system.  Zheng Minhua cited 'antibiotics that cause allergies, blood pressure that won't go down, anaesthetised patients who won't sleep' and laxatives that did not clear the bowel as being among the issues that had been encountered.  Dr Zheng's words immediately struck a chord and have been condensed into a social media slogan that has been viewed by millions in the past month - though much of the discussion of the topic has since been censored on Weibo. Many people have come forward to share their own bad experiences with alleged substandard drugs.  'I underwent intestinal surgeries in 2024, which required me to consume laxatives beforehand,' one Weibo user wrote. They said the drugs they were given had 'no effect whatsoever', even after the dose was doubled, and that they had to turn to drinking coffee to help clear their bowel. The concerns raised over the efficacy of generic drugs has caused distrust and made some people unwilling to use them.  A person on Xiaohongshu, China's Instagram-like app, said that when hospital doctors prescribed them the generic version of an antibiotic, they immediately went online to buy the 'original' 'real' one, since the generic version 'tasted different'.  'There have been many people catching colds recently. A lot of them might have bought this drug. Quickly send reminders to your friends now and get them to check the brand before buying,' the user warned.  Some of the most popular posts discussing the procurement controversy have been taken down, though it is unclear by whom. China's heavily monitored internet has a strong culture of censorship by both authorities and users themselves.  In a scathing, now-removed post by popular podcast host Meng Chang, he lambasted the lack of imported drugs in the public sector: 'If this isn't a bottom line, I don't know what is.'  Public anger has also been focussed on the difficulties of accessing imported drugs that people believe to be of better quality.  In response to authorities' attempt to reassure people of the quality of generic drugs, one Weibo user wrote: 'As long as we are allowed to buy brand-name drugs ourselves, I have no other complaints.'

With the Fed on hold, all eyes are on the long end, where they should be. It seems that the market is trying to decide between pricing in an era of endless deficit financing and rising term premia (which will take a bite of equity valuations), and pricing in an era of fiscal discipline, which would presumably keep the term premium under control. My guess is that the weekly jobless claims report will now become a key driver for bonds in the weeks ahead, as a measure of how much (or little) impact DOGE is having on government spending.

Ample liquidity may be good for stocks (and gold and bitcoin), but itâ€™s not welcomed by the bond vigilantes.  Global liquidity means rising deficits, which have to be financed.  Fiscal dominance is here, and without the Fed and other central banks mopping up the supply of Treasuries, the term premium has been rising and now stands at 84 bps. If the term premium returns to historically more appropriate levels (150 bps?), long Treasuries will easily sport a 5-handle.

Hereâ€™s a commercial I shot for Microsoft @surface as a Web2 KOL.  With over 5,000,000 followers on my Chinese social media accounts, @Forbes named me in the Forbes 30 Under 30 as a travel influencer. Since age 7, I authored two best-sellers, became @NBA LIVE commentator/field reporter, founded an influencer studio, and joined hands with tourism departments worldwide and top international brands.  Those brand deals let me see the whole world.  That was my student life.  Those years were fraught with anxiety.  I knew the KOL path wasn't right for me.   In the last 5 years, I graduated and shifted from @PwC  to Asset Management and Equity Research, from TradFi to crypto, moving from Seattle to Shanghai, Shenzhen, Hong Kong, and back to Seattle.   Every interview began with, â€œWhy did you quit being a successful KOL?â€  I had my answer ready.  In my eyes, marketing skills, when matched with another solid skill, are like a royal flush, but when played alone, they limit growth.  I craved a career that matured with age, rather than one where I had to weave new narratives for the brand sponsors and audience every passing year.  No matter how hard I pushed, the industry's confines remained, leaving me spinning in place.  All parties end.  Your time in the spotlight fades, but life goes on.  I need to understand why, after all those years, I remained just a KOL.  What mistakes did I make? I must avoid repeating them.   Looking back, my biggest failure was not leveraging and capitalizing my reach but relying solely on ad revenue. Ad revenue, though seemingly plentiful, is hard-earned, and control is never yours.  Year after year, I lived at the mercy of sponsors, facing waves of cheaper competitors undercutting the market.  My best years passed, yet my industry influence didn't grow with age.  KOLs, like actors and athletes, don't have careers that rise with age.  One must have a clear vision and a long-term plan.  Since 2022, I emptied everything and began anew in crypto.  I know the difference between a cherry on top and the foundation of life. Iâ€™m clear about whatâ€™s worth mastering and what isnâ€™t. I leave no gaps in my professional knowledge, skills, and resources, thinking through each step carefully and moving steadily.  People ask why I work tirelessly in crypto. I crossed mountains and rivers to find the right career path.  I'm finally on it now.  $URL[0]â€™

Someone asked me: 'How can you be so sure $NVDA is committing accounting fraud? Their Free Cash Flow growth says demand is real.'  Enron used to collateralise its SPEs with Enron stock and take out cash. It was an unending gravy train until the banks cut off credit. Nvidia hides its problems in off-balance sheet liabilities, thus generating the FCF illusion.  Looking at just one metric or another does not reveal the true picture. You don't simply get to a $3.5 trillion market cap without being a master manipulator.   Bernie Madoff is no fool and it took him about two decades to swindle investors out of $65 billion. Today, the Fed can print $65 billion in a day and nobody would even blink.  Germany's WireCard didn't even make it to a $30 billion market cap. China's Sino-Forest got up to $6.2 billion. Canada's Bre-X got to C$6 billion. Frauds are usually small, which is why no one is incentivized to catch them.  How Nvidia managed to reach into the trillions is going to be a book someday. No point in speculating on the how, that's up to PwC to figure out. There's no fresh data or insight I can add - either my explanations (and that of others on FinTwit) makes sense by now or it doesn't.

Satoshi modeled bitcoin after gold. He even used the word mining to describe the coinbase transaction (every bitcoin block begins with a miner reward).  But there's a key difference: if all the gold miners ceased operations today, gold will still have value.   If all the bitcoin miners went offline, the value of bitcoin goes to zero. Yes, zero. All bitcoin HODLers will own is an unspent transaction output on a defunct chain, which can never be transferred or spent.   But that will never happen, right?  11 bitcoin mining pools control the entire network. Bitcoin mining is super capital intensive, highly concentrated, and therefore, extremely vulnerable.  Decentralization in bitcoin is a myth. Bitcoin's $1.2 trillion market cap is built on a mining network worth around $25 billion, a mere 40% of the market cap of gold miner Newmont $NEM.  The bitcoin network is very, very fragile and at the mercy of a few giants.  Gold mining is global and decentralized, but even if all mining is somehow banned, the yellow metal isn't reliant on the mining industry and will carry on as it always has - as a  store of value and a monetary asset that's no one else's liability.  If you really understand the principles behind bitcoin, you'll see why gold is currently a superior asset. Even if you don't understand the history of money, the price action says it all - gold is making all-time highs, bitcoin isn't.  Gold has won the battle.

Did you know that Service Dogs are one of the most helpful aids for Veterans suffering from PTSD?  Yet, there isn't a single benefit or service offered through Veteran's Affairs Canada to assist vets in acquiring one.  Rather, they prefer to offer copious drugs or MAiD.  A service dog doesn't only offer companionship. Far from it.  Studies have shown (particularly in the case of operational stress injuries including PTSD) that there are many positive impacts for Veterans with PTSD after acquiring the service dog including decreased nightmares, improved sleep, fewer depressive symptoms and more social integration in the community.   For a veteran trying to reintegrate themselves into society after returning from a theater and suffering from an OSi, knowing someone has their 6 is more important than most people know. And a service dog provides that security.  @speyer8868 and I were speaking earlier today about it. I think this would be something we can petition VAC to make a change in offering to Veterans who need it. While VAC has done some research into it, I have seen the positive impacts myself from a service dog to vets, and highly advocate for it.  @erinotoole, you were Minister of VAC, and I'm sure still have contacts within. What would you say to helping us make some inroads for some positive change within VAC to help Veterans, and effect their mental state? Particularly this month, when theres a spotlight on Men's Mental Health?  @speyer8868 And I already have the contacts and the studies to back them and would be happy to help this as a cause with our systems to help in any way.   $URL[0]

Chinese investors flee from convertible bonds  2024 has seen a rout from convertible bonds - long considered a redoubt of safety in China's capital market, following a string of risk incidents and defaults starting from the middle of the year.   The current plunge in Chinese convertible bonds first commenced in mid-May, when Dongguan-based fashion brand Souyute became the first major issuer to materially default on a convertible bond.   Prior to that convertible bonds had long been viewed as safe haven investments with a track record of almost 'zero defaults' for more than three decades - essentially covering the entire history of China's capital market development.   Souyute was followed by a string of other 'risk incidents' in relation to convertible bonds, triggering intense trepidation on the Chinese debt market and putting heavy downward pressure on prices.   Sun Binbin (å­™å½¬å½¬), chief  fixed income analyst at Tiangfeng Securities, see opportunities in convertible bonds next year, however, following this exodus by Chinese investors.   'We suggest seizing opportunities created by the low valuation of convertible bonds,' Sun wrote in a recent online opinion piece, highlighting convertible bond ETFs in particular.  Source:  $URL[0]

â˜€ï¸â˜€ï¸ğŸŒ»Good Monday Morning!ğŸŒ»â˜€ï¸â˜€ï¸                                          and ğŸŒ»ğŸŒ»â˜€ï¸Happy Mindful Monday! ğŸŒ»ğŸŒ»â˜€ï¸  Today's Mindful Motivation: Compliments are Verbal Sunshine!  Yesterday while out shopping at Home Goods with two of my daughters, a random older woman was walking towards me with her cart. I tried to get out of her way, but she kept coming directly at me. I politely said excuse me, nodded and moved my cart in complete other direction to avoid her. But as she passed me, she gently grabbed my arm and said, 'Dear, I just wanted to tell you that you have beautiful legs! And I don't mean that in any sexual way.' I said 'Oh my goodness, thank you so much! You just made my day!' I was smiling from ear to ear and pulling my already long biking shorts down towards my knees. ğŸ˜‚ She said 'Oh no...if you got them, rock them!' I said, 'Thank you so much! Really. Thank you!'  Needless to say, I headed straight towards the checkout line. I don't know why. I just did. My daughters were laughing, but with caution, trying to catch up to me, asking me what she said. Being the little protective lionesses that I raised them to be. ğŸ¥° When I told them what she said, they just laughed and said 'Awe that was so sweet. Mom!' I said, 'I know, I know.'   The truth is, I wanted to cry. The struggle of how hard it is to maintain muscle and muscle tone as you age is very real. What use to be so natural and come easy to me now only comes with hard work, sweat and sometimes random, and I do mean random, pain! In that moment, my heart was overwhelmed, I was overwhelmed, with joy and gratitude for a complete stranger. She genuinely made my day. She has no idea just how much that meant to me, but I hope she saw it in my face and heard it in my voice.   Never underestimate the power of a genuine random compliment. Don't be afraid to handout sincere compliments! It costs absolutely nothing, but can mean so much to someone else.   #MondayMotivation #MondayThoughts #Mindfullness #CoffeeTime #CoffeeLovers

Eridu, the second evoled city and a city of water. 5500 - 2000 BC. ğŸ’§  The people of Catalhoyuk, who lived in the first city, could not utilize river water.  However, the citizens of the city of Eridu utilized the Euphrates River water for irrigation agriculture and secured the water resources of the Persian Gulf.  The citizens of Catalhoyuk failed to create an economic system for their city.  However, the citizens of Eridu operated the city's economy centered around the temple, with priests managing it.

The samara culture connected the upstream river cultures with the downstream river cultures. 5500 - 4800 BC. ğŸ’§  The Samarra culture formed in the region between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers.  They were influenced by the Hassuna culture, located upstream of Euphrated River.  Like the Halaf people, who were central to the Hassuna culture, they also practiced irrigated agriculture.  The center of the Samarra culture was Sawwan, located  on the Tigris River.  They played a role in connecting the people of the upstream rivers with those of the downstream rivers.  After 4800 BC, the Samarra culture was absorbed into the more advanced downstream culture, the Ubaid cultures.

RT @histories_arch: Shiva as Nataraja, the Lord of Dance, is a powerful symbol in Hindu mythology. Imagine a figure dancing within a circle of fire, representing the endless cycle of creation and destruction. This image of Shiva, dating back to around the 10th century CE, shows him with four arms, each holding a different object that signifies his cosmic powers.  India is a land where music and dance are woven into the fabric of everyday life. People sing and dance with elephants during festivals, and even in their movies, a sudden burst of song and dance is a common sight. Anything happen and they start dancing; Dance is not just entertainment; itâ€™s a way of expressing joy, telling stories, and connecting with the divine.  Shivaâ€™s dance, known as the Tandava, is a cosmic performance that keeps the universe in balance. Itâ€™s a reminder of how important dance is in Indian culture, from ancient temples to cinema. So, next time you see a dance scene in an Indian cinema, remember itâ€™s part of a tradition that goes back thousands of years.  #archaeohistories

Evidence of growing collateral difficulties clearly tied to market perceptions of rising - not falling - US recession risks.   Repo fails up + Japanese govt bill yields down.   How do we get from US$  to Japan 3m bills and back to US recession?  1. Japanese government bill rates trading below Bank of Japan's overnight rate signaling high demand for that specific instrument.  2. Connection between US dollar repo collateral and Japanese government bills is via the real Japan 'carry trade.'   3. Japanese borrowing in US$ repo using UST collateral (borrowed) encounter collateral scarcity essentially swap collateral via FX allowing them to use yen instead.  4. US$ lenders in FX take the yen collateral and park it in safe liquid yen investments, such as 3m govt bills.   5. IOW, when USTs are increasing scarce as collateral we see the end result of the FX rerouting as suddenly higher demand for Japan 3m bills (this tenor in particular).   6. Trend since early August shows continuous rise in repo fails, with corresponding drop in Japanese government bill rates, highlighting collateral challenges therefore both tied to 'carry trade' unwinding.  7. Carry trade unwinding was triggered by US recession risks (several Japanese firms, i.e, the carry traders themselves) have gone on the record saying US recession risks are higher than the media is talking about after a single (unreliable) payroll number.   8. Historical patterns link US dollar repo fails, collateral difficulties, and Japanese Bill yields, revealing systemic fragility and interdependence. This has gone for over a decade with repeated results.   End. Understanding the intricate relationship between US dollar repo, collateral shortages, and Japanese financial instruments crucial for assessing macro risks. Why would the Ukrainians attack a Russian early warning radar station?  On May 24, 2024, the Ukrainian SBU conducted a long-rage OWUAV strike on the â€œVeronezh-DMâ€ Early Warning Radar Station in #Armavir, Krasnodar Krai, Russia, at geolocation 44.925287, 40.983854. Both of the radars there (one faces SW and the other SE) were struck in the attack and, based on review of photos/videos from after the attack, appeaar to have been rendered inoperative. Here are some potential reasons for the attack:  1) It forces the Russians to reposition their dwindling air defense systems to protect a whole new class of strategic targets on their own soil. This would then lessen their pressence in/near Ukraine which, among other things, helps to shape the airspace there for the successful deployment of AFU F-16's.   2) It costs money and resources to repair the radar systems which diverts them from supporting Russias on the ground.  3) The SW (westernmost radar) covers the airspace over southern Ukraine and the western coast of Krasnodar Krai, Russia, out to a range of about 6,000 kilometers. Destroying that radar, along with the destruction of the several Russian A-50 AWACs and their subsequent grouding, opens the airspace for ballistic missile and drone attacks on juicy targets like the Crimean Bridge and the BSF Naval Base in #Novorossiysk, Krasnodar Krai, Russia.  #OSINT #UkraineRussiaWar #UkraineWar #UkraineKrieg #Ukraine #Russia

Showdown in the Pacific: US vs. China Military Analysis  The hypothetical scenario of a military confrontation between the United States and China raises complex questions about the capabilities, strategies, and potential outcomes of such a conflict. Both nations possess formidable military forces with significant strengths and capabilities. The United States boasts the world's most advanced and technologically sophisticated military, including a dominant naval presence, a global network of bases, and advanced air and space capabilities. China, on the other hand, has invested heavily in modernizing its military, particularly its naval and missile forces, as part of its efforts to assert regional dominance in the Asia-Pacific region. While the United States maintains an edge in terms of overall military capabilities and technological superiority, China's rapidly expanding military capabilities, including its anti-access/area denial (A2/AD) capabilities and growing arsenal of advanced missiles, present significant challenges.  In a hypothetical military confrontation between the two powers, the outcome would depend on various factors, including the nature of the conflict, the theater of operations, and the strategies employed by both sides. The United States would likely seek to leverage its strengths in air and naval power, combined with its network of allies and partners, to maintain maritime superiority and project power into the Asia-Pacific region. However, China's A2/AD capabilities, including advanced anti-ship missiles and ballistic missiles, could pose significant challenges to US forces operating in the region, particularly in contested areas such as the South China Sea.  Moreover, any military conflict between the United States and China would carry immense risks and potential consequences, including the escalation of hostilities, significant loss of life, and catastrophic economic and geopolitical ramifications. As such, both nations have a vested interest in avoiding direct military confrontation and pursuing diplomatic and strategic avenues for managing and mitigating tensions. While the United States maintains significant military advantages over China, the complexities and uncertainties surrounding a potential conflict underscore the importance of diplomacy, dialogue, and cooperation in maintaining peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific region.  Via: The Military Show  #SecurityAnalysis #PacificShowdown #Geopolitics

RT @JoshEakle: This father went to his citizenship hearing expecting a handshake.  Instead, ICE shackled him, threw him into a van, and tore him away from his pregnant wife and four childrenâ€”without even letting him say goodbye.  Kasper Eriksen arrived in Mississippi from Denmark in 2013, fully documented and determined to build a life here.  He started a family, became part of his community, and followed every rule. He was never accused, let alone convicted, of any crime.  But as best we understand, he's now imprisoned because of a single clerical mistake made years ago. In 2015, Kasper and his wife, Savannah, missed filing one form, among the hundreds required on the complicated path to citizenship.  Savannah had just suffered a stillbirth, losing their first child. In the painful days that followed, paperwork deadlines understandably slipped past unnoticed.  Now, over a month after his arrest, Kasper remains locked in a detention facility notorious for cruelty, neglect, and abuse.  Savannahâ€”eight months pregnant, at high risk, and terrifiedâ€”is desperately pleading for her husband's return.  She and their children have no idea when or if they'll ever see him again, and she doesn't know if he'll be present for her child's birth. The death of the 'Zangezur Corridor' is nearÖ‰ Russia's new defeat? After the last war against Nagorno Karabakh, Turkey, Azerbaijan and Russia will most likely stop making territorial claims to #Armenia under the name of the 'Zangezur Corridor.' The President of Turkey Erdogan, made an statement today on the issue of the regional blockade.   It's likely that we are dealing with a turning point. Erdogan hinted that the 'Zangezur Corridor' may not be on the territory of Armenia.   'Establishing direct land and railway connections with #Nakhichevan and other regions of #Azerbaijan will further strengthen our relations. That's why we will do everything to open this corridor as soon as possible. The implementation of this corridor is very important for #Turkey and #Azerbaijan, it's a strategic issue and must be completed.   When this corridor is opened, a car or train leaving #Baku will be able to come directly to #Kars. It's gratifying to see positive signals from Iran in this matter. The railway passes through Turkey to Nakhichevan, Armenia, and Azerbaijan. If Armenia doesn't give way, where does it go? It goes through #Iran. Iran now looks positively at that issue' said Erdogan.   The President of Turkey said that the issue of the regional blockade should be resolved without conflict and noise. 'If we want the corridors of #Zangezur and #Lachin to become corridors of #peace, we must solve this issue without conflict and noise. If Armenia is against it, that road will pass through Iran. Iran now looks positively at that issue.'   This new statement by #Erdogan may mean that Turkey, Azerbaijan, and Russia will abandon the plan to obtain the '#ZangezurCorridor' by force against Armenia. Iran and the #USA have a very big role in that matter.  Today #US Secretary of State Anthony Blinken had a telephone conversation with President of Azerbaijan Ilham #Aliyev. The telephone conversation took place at the initiative of the #American side. The US Secretary of State emphasized that there should be no more #military operations. Aliyev assured that there will be no military operations.   Yesterday, the spokesperson of the US State Department Matthew Miller informed that the US and Turkey, among others, are also discussing the issue of the so-called 'Zangezur Corridor'. Miller noted that the US is working with the Turkish government on this issue: 'This was one of the issues that Secretary of State Blinken discussed with his Turkish counterpart during a meeting in New York last Friday. We hope that all our allies and partners can play a constructive role in reaching a lasting agreement, including Turkey.'  From the words of the spokesperson of the US State Department, we can conclude that the US worked with Turkey in order not to demand the 'Zangezur Corridor' from Armenia. That's what Erdogan's words about not going into a new conflict confirm. It's no coincidence that after the meeting with Blinken last Friday in New York, Erdogan, while returning from Nakhichevan, said that if Armenia doesn't want, the 'Zangezur Corridor' can pass through Iran.   We can conclude that the USA has warned #Turkey about the need to stop the pressure on Armenia regarding the 'Zangezur Corridor'. Previously, Turkey definitely considered that the 'Zangezur Corridor' should pass through the territory of Armenia.  And what is official Armenia's point of view on the 'Zangezur Corridor' issue, and would it like that road to pass through its territory? On the day of Ilham #Aliyev and Erdogan's meeting in Nakhichevan, Minister of Territorial Administration and Infrastructure Gnel Sanosyan announced that Armenia has never agreed and will not agree to any extraterritorial or corridor logic.   'Armenia has never agreed to any extraterritorial or corridor logic and will never agree. But we are committed to the agreements reached at a high level. On July 15, during the meeting of the leaders of Armenia and Azerbaijan, the following agreements were reaffirmed:  Armenia and Azerbaijan recognize each other's territorial integrity with an area of 29.8 and 86.6 thousand square kilometers, respectively.  The delimitation of the border between Armenia and Azerbaijan will take place on the basis of the 1991 Alma Ata Declaration.  Regional communications should be unblocked based on the principles of sovereignty, jurisdiction, and reciprocity of the parties.  These agreements are public and were announced by the President of the European Council, Charles Michel, at the end of the meeting. Within the framework of this agreement, the Republic of Armenia is not only ready for the unblocking of communications, but also wants it to happen as quickly as possible, because it's in our interests' said the Minister of Territorial Administration and Infrastructures of Armenia.  Thus, the Armenian Minister has answered Erdogan's question: does #Yerevan agree to the opening of the 'Zangezur Corridor' or not? Turkey and Azerbaijan must respect Armenia's sovereignty and jurisdiction over that road, and in that case, the road will be opened.  At the meeting of the leaders of Armenia and Azerbaijan expected in #Granada at the beginning of October, it will be clear whether Azerbaijan will abandon the strategy of presenting a territorial claim to Armenia under the name of 'Zangezur Corridor' or not. If Turkey and Azerbaijan decide to no longer present a territorial claim to Armenia, and accept Armenia's jurisdiction over that road, there will be no problem in the matter of lifting the blockade. Armenia shouldn't be asked to deploy Russian military forces on that road. It's also a red line for the Armenian side.  There's a risk that even after capturing #NagornoKarabakh, Azerbaijan will blockade Armenia. Turks and Azerbaijanis may prefer to connect through the territory of Iran, so that Azerbaijan doesn't undertake to allow Armenia to have railway and automobile connections with Russia through its territory. If the real goal of Azerbaijan is peace, it should open its roads for Armenia as well.  If Turkey and Azerbaijan make a decision to pass the 'Zangezur Corridor' through Iran, then Russia is left out of the game. On May 25, 2023, Ilham Aliyev, participating in the EEU session, revealed that the 'Zangezur Corridor' is his idea, and Baku has Russia's support in this matter. In recent days, Russia made great efforts to convince Iran to agree to the opening of the Zangezur Corridor.   On the day of Azerbaijan's attack on Nagorno #Karabakh, on September 20, Russian Defense Minister Sergey Shoigu visited Iran, where, for sure, the possibility of the 'Zangezur Corridor' was discussed with Mohammad Reza Ashtiani, the Minister of Defense of the Iran.  However, Russia failed to convince Iran to open the 'Zangezur Corridor'. At the moment when Erdogan and Aliyev met in Nakhichevan on September 25, the Prime Minister of Armenia received the Iranian Ambassador Mehdi Sobhan, who once again emphasized the clear position of the Iranian side regarding the protection of Armenia's territorial integrity.  Iran previously announced at the highest level that the territorial integrity of Armenia is a red line and they will not allow changes in the borders. The spiritual leader of Iran received Erdogan and #Putin in July 2022. At the meeting with the leaders of Russia and Turkey, Ayatollah #Khamenei publicly opposed the opening of the Zangezur Corridor. I believe that the positions of Iran and the USA give grounds for asserting that the probability of opening the 'Zangezur Corridor' by war has greatly decreased.  In fact, #Washington and #Tehran support Armenia not to provide an extraterritorial corridor to Russia, Turkey, and Azerbaijan. But as I said, we still have to wait for the meeting of Nikol Pashinyan, Ilham Aliyev, Emmanuel Macron, Olaf Scholz, Charles Michel in Granada and the results of the negotiations. If it is possible to establish in the peace agreement a clause on lifting the blockade while preserving the territorial integrity and sovereignty of Armenia, it can be argued that Russia will suffer another defeat.   'Zangezur Corridor', on which #Moscow intended to deploy Russian armed forces, will not be created. In the initial version of Putin's statement of November 9, 2020, there was a clause about creating the 'Zangezur Corridor' and deploying Russian armed forces, but it was removed at the request of Armenia. We are currently dealing with the death of the November 9, 2020 announcement.   The September 19 Azeri attack on Nagorno Karabakh destroyed the architecture planned by Putin in the South Caucasus. This mechanically means the destruction of the false basis for demanding 'Zangezur Corridor' from Armenia.

: : Key Players of Interest to Research within the Solana Ecosystem  After Breakpoint, my feed has been filled with news about Solana. I believe this isnâ€™t just a result of a biased algorithm but reflects the genuinely strong narrative around Solana in CT.  I'm not particularly fond of general conferences with vague themes, as the content presented by various protocols often feels more like marketing than showcasing new features. However, Breakpoint was differentâ€”each seemed to have put a lot of effort into preparing for the event. I could genuinely feel the enthusiasm as all ecosystem players aligned with Solana's overarching vision, passionately pitching their new features and fostering collaboration.  As a researcher, my initiatives to contribute to the Solana ecosystem moving forward will be: 1) deriving insights from various initiatives on the Solana network (e.g., Token Extension, Mobile, Payment, etc.), and 2) specifically highlighting each of key players that will drive the future of the Solana ecosystem.  The research areas (or teams) I plan to focus on, or the protocols I hope to continue collaborating with, are as follows:  1. Infrastructure & Development Tools  Squads  @SquadsProtocol is a custody layer solution that enables safer asset management and operation, providing standards for various smart accounts, including asset management, permission settings, and multi-signature.  Pyth Network  @PythNetwork is an oracle network providing real-time primary financial market data essential for DeFi services on the blockchain. It recently announced that it will introduce an Oracle Integrity Staking (OIS) delegation mechanism, which will reward Pyth stakers while enabling the network to secure high-quality data from publishers for DeFi projects.  Metaplex  @metaplex is a representative library that provides various tools/standards for creating / managing digital assets in the Solana Ecosystem.  The team recently launched an indexing and data availability network called Aura Network - this network allows users not only to easily store and retrieve data, but also to flexibly manage the state within the Solana and SVM ecosystems, and perform multi-program consistent indexing via the enhanced Digital Asset Standard (DAS) API.  Usecases for ZK Compression  ZK Compression, currently being developed by the @LightProtocol and @heliuslabs teams, is a technology that combines zero-knowledge proofs (ZKPs) with state compression, which reduces the size of states. This technology aims to drastically reduce the operational costs of data and accounts on the Solana network and create an environment where more complex ZK-friendly applications, such as identity verification protocols, can be developed.  The Helius team recently announced AirShip, a large-scale airdrop tool powered by ZK Compression.  SVM Support/Leverage Projects ( @soon_svm , @EclipseFND , @Terminaxyz , etc )  As Solana's SVM demonstrates superior transaction processing capabilities compared to other mainnets, more and more projects are emerging with the desire to build their own ecosystems based on the SVM execution environment, without needing to share composability, ledger data, or other infrastructure components of the Solana network.  Infrastructure that leverages/supports SVM will be key cases to demonstrate whether SVM can position itself as a competitive VM in the market dynamics.  Tinydancer  The Solana network lacks a light client feature that allows for state validation without running a full node, limiting its validation capabilities. To address this, @tinydancerio , a light client under development, enables transaction verification at a low cost without downloading the entire block or executing transactions. It alerts the full node it depends on when suspicious transactions are detected.  Verifiable Computing ( @ArciumHQ , @Bonsolsh )  Verifiable Compute (VC) allows specific workloads to generate proofs of execution that can be publicly verified without rerunning the computation - a key practical application with this is that it helps developers mitigate the rising costs of on-chain product logic by moving computations off-chain. In other words, by using VC, one can quickly and efficiently implement applications that require complex logic, such as Oracle, Lending, RWA, etc. It also allows you to implement business logic while keeping certain critical information hidden.  Payments( @sphere_labs , @getcode , @TipLinkOfficial , @helio_pay , etc)  Solana has established itself as the most suitable blockchain for the crypto payment sector, thanks to its parallel processing through multi-threading, fast transaction speeds, and low transaction costs. It is actively strengthening initiatives in this space (e.g., Token Extension, Blinks) to make blockchain transactions as intuitive and simple as credit card payments.  Various payment-related projects are aligning with these initiatives by developing SDKs that allow end-users to easily make crypto payments across different contexts (i.e., web and mobile environments).  2. Finance & Consumer Applications  ISC  ISC (International Stable Currency, @ISC_money ) is a stablecoin project built on Solana, aiming to provide users with a stable, internationally recognized currency that can be used both online and offline. Unlike traditional stablecoins pegged to fiat currencies like the US dollar, ISC is linked to real assets such as commodities, bonds, and stocks, offering inflation-resistant characteristics.  Perena  @Perena__ is building decentralized infrastructure for money on Solana. Perena aims to enhance the usability, liquidity, and rewards of stablecoins within DeFi, where its mission focuses on facilitating frictionless exchange of dollar-pegged assets and maximizing yield generation for idle stablecoin liquidity.  Sky Ecosystem  @SkyEcosystem , formerly known as MakerDAO, is a DeFi protocol planning to expand into the Solana DeFi ecosystem by integrating its USDS (stablecoin) and SKY (governance token) through Wormhole. Recently, they announced an incentive program aimed at bootstrapping and activating the Solana DeFi ecosystem, allocating 2 million SKY tokens per week.  Magic Eden  @MagicEden is the dominant NFT marketplace on Solana, and supports a multi-chain environment including Ethereum, Polygon, and Bitcoin Ordinals, offering launchpads for each project or BTC Inscriptions. The launch of the ME token, designed to support and encourage the trading of different assets across various chains, is scheduled in the near future.  Tensor  @tensor_hq is a NFT marketplace especially tailored for professional NFT traders on Solana, integrating AMM and marketplace functionalities. Users can access real-time data, candlestick-priced AMMs for NFTs, and employ various trading strategies, including mass acquisition, bidding, listing/delisting of NFTs.  Recently, TensorÂ announcedÂ the full open-sourcing of its code, a grant program, a restructuring of its fee model, and the preview of a new product line calledÂ $URL[0]  Sanctum  @sanctumso is a solution that allows all Liquid Staking Tokens (LST) projects within the Solana ecosystem to share liquidity with each other, allowing for seamless interactions between each LST (e.g., zero slippage), or users can also earn revenue by supplying liquidity of a specific LST to the Sanctum Infinity pool.  Sanctum is planning to addÂ two more products related to PayFiÂ - 1) Creator Coins, which will enable organizations and individuals to easily build, grow, and monetize their communities, and 2) Cloud Card, a card product line that allows users to utilize SOL and various stablecoins in over 100 countries.  Jito  @jito_labs not only powers the Jito-Solana client, which dominates the Solana MEV marketplace, but also leads the LST (Liquid Staking Token) market by running a Liquid Staking project (i.e., jitoSOL) that ensures the MEV share allocations can be distributed to stakers.  In July, they released the code forÂ their staking and restaking programs as a open-source, and also plans to apply a permissionless model to the operation of the JitoSOL pool via StakeNet.  Fragmetric  @fragmetric is the first liquid restaking protocol in the Solana ecosystem, aiming to enhance the liquidity and composability of staked assets. Its main product, fragSOL, is a Solana-native LRT (Liquid Restaking Token) based on Jito's Restaking Vault Receipt Token (VRT) system.  Drift  @DriftProtocol is a decentralized trading platform built on Solana, with itsÂ V2 upgradeÂ focusing on improving order execution speed and market efficiency. Users can engage in various activities such as spot trading, perpetual trading, borrowing and lending, and passive liquidity provision in real-time updating markets. Recently, it also launched a prediction market called â€œBETâ€.  Jupiter  @JupiterExchange is the leading DEX Aggregator on Solana, providing the best and cheapest routes for trading on Solana. The platform primarily offers features such as limit orders, futures trading, dollar-cost averaging (DCA), fiat on-ramp, and bridging.  In addition, Jupiter offers or plans to offer various features, such as - 'LFG Launchpad,' which has supported the launch of protocols like Sanctum, Zeus, and SharkyFi; 2) â€˜$URL[1]â€™ a feature that simplifies the minting and trading of new tokens, as seen withÂ $URL[2] and 3) â€˜easy on-ramp mobile integrationâ€™ through solutions like Apple Pay, credit cards, and Google Pay.'  FluxBeamÂ &Â FluxBot  @FluxBeamDEX is the DEX that supports trading of all types of Solana tokens, including SPL, SPL404, and SPL22. Users can perform token swaps, provide liquidity, and bridge assets as basic functions. In addition, FluxBeam offers token creation and management tools, enabling developers and users to easily handle tokens within the Solana ecosystem.  It also provides a Telegram trading bot called FluxBot ( @Fluxbeam_bot ), which includes features like token sniping, copy trading, etc.  Cube Exchange  @cubexch is a leading hybrid decentralized exchange (HEX) that provides efficient, secure, and compliant trading experiences by leveraging Multi-Party Computation (MPC) technology to combine off-chain order matching with on-chain settlements.  The teamÂ is planning to launch Isometric Network, an intent-based network, built upon the technology stack previously applied atÂ $URL[3]Â (i.e., MPC, two-tiered validator consensus, multi-chain settlement, etc.).  Seeker & Mobile Stack  Solana Mobile Stack (SMS) is an open-source SDK that provides tools (e.g., Solana dApp Store, Mobile Wallet Adapter, Seed Vault, Solana Pay) for developing applications on mobile devices such as Saga and Seeker.  Through the mobile devices, which have Solanaâ€™s various protocol-level technologies and ecosystem applications natively embedded, end users can enjoy a seamless and integrated on-chain experience.  ORE  @OREsupply is a proof-of-work (PoW) based digital currency within the Solana ecosystem, designed to ensure fair and accessible mining.  3.DePIN & AI  WayFinder AI  @AIWayfinder is a decentralized protocol of user-owned, autonomous AI agents that enables them to navigate and operate across on-chain applications and ecosystems.  Grass  @getgrass_io is a DePIN that aims to democratize AI model training through a distributed network of incentivized nodes that share unused bandwidth to collect and process web data.  GrassÂ desktopÂ node is available for higher efficiency, and Solana wallet addresses have beenÂ integratedÂ with users' Grass accounts, ensuring that rewards are distributed to nodes when their data is used for AI inference or training tasks.  Privasea  @Privasea_ai aims to encrypt and protect sensitive data by utilizing various Fully Homomorphic Encryption (FHE) techniques. Notably, the Privasea team has developed a dApp called 'ImHuman,' which allows users to locally store and encrypt their biometric data as NFTs, enabling them to prove their humanity and protect themselves from malicious bots and programs.  â€”  If there are any projects you would like me to cover more, or if you're considering collaboration with @FourPillarsFP, feel free to DM me ğŸ™  *For a comprehensive article about the key announcements at Breakpoint and a well-organized overview of Solana, check out the 89-minute mega report I wrote: $URL[4]  **If you're looking for detailed updates from individual players, you can refer to past threads or YouTube videos ( $URL[5] ) from the official @solana account. You can also find great summaries in threads from @SolanaFloor.

Please indulge me in a thought experiment. Not a prediction or even a claim.   What if the current acrimony between the US & China is a huge pa de deux, with all the seeming misteps, gaffes, outrages and U-turns scripted and agreed by both sides in advance?  What if they all realize the urgent need to rebalance the world's military, geopolitical, and geo-economic power, but need to do so without losing local legitimacy?   So they proceed like they are proceeding now, with the US side looking like a loser to the Chinese (and to the non-MAGA Americans) while appearing crafty and 'art-of-the-dealish' to MAGA.   What if they understand that in the coming world of AI and robotics, 'overcapacity' will be a part of the human condition? And not just in goods. We're not talking about increased productivity, but about univeral *hyperproductivity*, and not just in manufactured goods, but in all kinds of services (think about the downstream implications of open-sourced Deepseek and similar offerings to SAAS, and what happens to companies whose chief advantage is in 'traditional' R&D). Tariffs and sanctions won't matter much.  Once again it's just a thought experiment, but what if all this is attendant to protracted, overarching negotiations (already secretly in progress) that will see a contraction the US  military footprint in East Asia (boots on the ground will be largely obsolete and expensive anyway) appropriate Chinese alignment/assistance on geopolitical issues, agreements on currency valuation, debt levels, security, etc.?  And what if the news from this operation, the individual tit-for-tat, the standing firm, the pivots and deflections, and, finally, the many discreet agreements (in principle) are doled out to the respective publics so we all perceive it as do the proverbial blind men describing an elephant?  Of course this would pre-suppose a lot, mainly the existance of benificent gods above those visible on Mount Olympus and on TV.

Dear @GovRonDeSantis,   Part of me regrets not saying this to you face-to-face when you graciously signed my copy of your book, but you were pressed for time as always, and as my Texas brother door-knocker from another mother would be quick to tell  you (Cooper @yankees_28th in the background behind your inscription), I can go long once I get started.  So please bear with me while I get this off my chest. My late father, Floyd V. Amoresano, was a fellow alum of yours - Harvard Law Class of '39, Cum Laude (His Profs wrote the books from which the rest of us lawyers have studied).  In addition, his Italian roots are from regions (Montecorice and Calabria) not far from your own. Like you, when war broke out, he enlisted - Army 1st Lt., Fort Monmouth, NJ - and served in a unit within the Signal Corps which played an important role in the interception and de-coding of enemy messages.  In 1964, when I was 11 years old, my dad sat me down with him to watch Reagan's now infamous 'Time for Choosing' speech....   Fast forward 40 years, and I'm on a train to DC with my brother, then standing on line, outside, overnight, for over 10 hours, to earn the privilege of spending 5 precious minutes praying over Reagan's flag-draped coffin, lying in state beneath the dome of the Capitol Rotunda. I'm sharing this with you now to make certain you appreciate the full weight of what I want to convey: For me, and for so many others, you are the one to whom Providence has passed Reagans torch.  You sir. No other.  Not even close. THAT is why Cooper and I banged on doors for you in a bitter-cold blizzard, and did so with overflowing joy in our hearts, on account of having been afforded the privilege just to be a small part of your noble mission - to continue the fight of our Founding Fathers for The Sacred Fires of Liberty. They told us that student loan repayments would crash the economy.  They cried about commercial real estate.  They cried about auto loans.  They tried to tell us that the ETFs wouldn't unlock demand.  They used their big brains to discredit the market, and their big brains failed them while you just consistently outperformed them.  Their ego can't take it because it requires them to admit that they've lost and that their precious intelligence failed them.  To avoid this reality, they operate with extreme cognitive dissonance.  They lash out.  They scream and cry even louder.  They proclaim that the market is a bubble.  They attribute our success to dumb luck.  And they continue to underperform.  It becomes a recursive cycle of doom & pessimism.  Even when asset prices fall, like in March & April, they claim that more pain is coming around the corner.  I've never once heard a Doomer say 'U.S. equities are cheap now'.  When stocks rise, they say it's unjustified.  When stocks fall, they say it's justified & will get worse.  They do the same with Bitcoin.  So, as these 'investors' inevitably get louder and louder, it's our job to completely ignore them or use them as contra indicators and fade them.  To give yourself the best chance at success as an investor, you must avoid their pessimistic mentality.  I'm speaking from experience here, as a former Doomer.  Good luck.

RT @EismanSteven: VP Harris proposes to give eligible Americans $25k to purchase a home.  This is one of her major initiatives to make housing more affordable and hereâ€™s why that proposal wonâ€™t come close to working.   There is definitely a shortage of homes for sale and this shortage is a major reason for housing price escalation.  There are two issues here.  First, not enough existing homes are being sold.  Second, it costs too much and takes too long to build homes.  Letâ€™s look at each of these problems.  With respect to existing homes, during Covid, when interest rates collapsed, every homeowner refinanced into a 3% mortgage.  Current mortgage rates have oscillated between 6.5% and 7.5%.  For a buyer to have the same monthly payment as the seller, housing prices would need to decline by 50%.  But the economy is strong and people are employed.  Employed people are not distressed sellers.  So the existing housing market is locked.  Unfortunately, there is no policy that can solve this problem other than significantly lower interest rates.  Maybe that will happen and maybe it wonâ€™t but the federal government canâ€™t force the issue.  So the only game in town is new homes.  It is true that the U.S. does not build enough new homes.  There are many reason why but an important one is that building new homes requires complying with a myriad of state and local ordinances that just take time to deal with.  I donâ€™t think the federal government can do much here either.   What we have is a supply problem for both existing and new homes.  Itâ€™s NOT a demand problem.  Giving people who canâ€™t afford to buy home $25k just increases demand.  Low end housing prices will just go up more.  Iâ€™m sure there are better solutions.  But the $25k giveaway will only cause prices to go up. Who does that help?  Nobody.

ğŸ‡·ğŸ‡ºâ˜¢ï¸ What tactical nuclear weapons can Russia practice using in the announced exercises?  Tactical nuclear weapons, in contrast to strategic ones, are low-power charges that cannot turn an entire city into ashes, but are capable of causing very large damage, including radiation contamination of the area.  The nuclear warhead can be installed in 9M723-1 missiles of the Iskander-M complexes, as well as in 9M728 low-altitude cruise missiles. Their capacity can vary from 5 to 50 kt.  Such missiles can attack large logistics hubs, command and staff infrastructure, missile defense and other military installations.  It is also possible to strike the gateways of the bunker architecture in the Carpathians, where the Ukrainian Armed Forces can deploy some of the transferred F-16s.  Also, tactical nuclear warheads can be installed in the Kh-47M2 Kinzhal aeroballistic missiles (delivered by the MiG-31K and Tu-22M3), high-speed cruise missiles Kh-32 (carried by the Tu-22M3), Kh-69 and other air-launched cruise missiles.  Nuclear weapons in the form of shells with a nuclear charge can also be launched by barrel artillery: howitzers D-20, Akatsiya, Msta-B, Giatsint-B, Msta-S/SM, Malva and Koalitsiya- SV' (152 mm with a capacity of 2.5 kt); Self-propelled guns 'Pion' and 'Malka' (203 mm with a capacity of about 2 kt); self-propelled mortar 'Tulip' (240 mm, 2 kt, firing range - up to 18 km).  srochnow

Okay so I called AGI over 18 months ago, was pretty close.   I've been prompt engineering and finetuning since GPT-2.  Here's my current take:   2024 was Year 0, the real beginning of the wave (though many will remember ChatGPT as the first shot across the bow)   2025 is Year 1. That's the year that AI became commercially viable across most sectors, so we'll see a surge of early adopters next year (we're currently in the 'innovators' part of the curve now).   We'll see some huge strides in commercial humanoid robotics next year, along with everyone agreeing 'yeah, okay we have AGI for sure' though there will always be knuckledraggers moving the goalposts.   It'll be like drinking from the firehose more than it is today, but 2026 will be the year of Scorched Earth.   What I mean by that is that companies are gonna start imploding, those that fail to adapt. Think Borders. But also jobs attrition will likely be a hot topic for midterm elections (we're already seeing good jobs drying up, I suspect it will accelerate as AI capabilities increase and market penetration deepens).  So yeah, that's about what I'm confident in prediction for the next 18ish months in broad strokes.   AMA

Did you know Christian husbands can save the world in only ten minutes per day?  Okay. That is an exaggeration. But few evangelicals know you can take ground for the Kingdom, and obey the Lord in the leadership of your family, right from your kitchen table.  The practice of family worship has been exercised as long as mankind has known his Creator. In the present day, husbands and fathers can fulfill their duty to lead their wives and children in true religion by regularly setting aside time for prayer, reading of the Bible, singing, and similar means of worship.  'And these words that I command you today shall be on your heart. You shall teach them diligently to your children, and shall talk of them when you sit in your house, and when you walk by the way, and when you lie down, and when you riseâ€¦' (Deuteronomy 6:6-7).  'We will not hide them from their children, but tell to the coming generation the glorious deeds of the Lord, and his might, and the wonders that he has doneâ€¦' (Psalm 78:4).  'Husbands, love your wives, as Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her, that he might sanctify her, having cleansed her by the washing of water with the wordâ€¦' (Ephesians 5:25-26).  'Fathers, do not provoke your children to anger, but bring them up in the discipline and instruction of the Lordâ€¦' (Ephesians 6:4).  Most evangelical husbands assume that taking their families to church on Sunday is sufficient for their discipleship and formation in the Christian faith. Even as the entire family should be part of the life of the church, and although building these habits is important, we see from these texts and others that husbands should be far more intentional about family discipleship.  I was raised in an evangelical tradition where family worship was not discussed or expected. Now I cherish the time my wife and I spend worshiping together, and I cannot wait to welcome our future children into our traditions, should the Lord bless us in that way.  The most consistent methods for instilling a regular practice of family worship are simplicity and brevity. You can lead extended family worship times, but you can also spend ten minutes together, perhaps after dinner or before bed, moving through this very basic routine:   â€” Opening prayer  â€” Read one paragraph of the Bible  â€” Discuss the main points  â€” Pray for one or two specific requests  â€” Sing the Doxology or Gloria Patri  You can extend these elements as time and attention spans allow. Many families memorize catechism questions or sing psalms and hymns. Those are great elements to add.  You need not be intimidated by the prospect of leading through a book of the Bible. Consider walking your family through a book you recently studied during private worship. You can keep the discussion very simple and research later if your wife or child has a question you cannot answer.  I sincerely hope and pray that adopting a practice of family worship will bless your household as this practice has blessed mine.  Want to Christianize the world? Start by Christianizing your own household.  May the Lord Jesus Christ bless our culture with revival, and may that revival start around thousands upon thousands of kitchen tables.
